import java.io.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());

        int n = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
        int m = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

        long[] arr = new long[n];

        st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            arr[i] = Long.parseLong(st.nextToken());
        }

        long[] diff = new long[n + 2];

        for (int i = 0; i < m; i++) {
            st = new StringTokenizer(br.readLine());
            int l = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
            int r = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

            diff[l]++;
            diff[r + 1]--;
        }

        long[] counts = new long[n];
        long current = 0;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            current += diff[i];
            counts[i - 1] = current;
        }

        Arrays.sort(arr);
        Arrays.sort(counts);

        long total = 0;

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            total += arr[i] * counts[i];
        }

        System.out.println(total);
    }
}


🔴 Why Scanner Is Slow

When you write:

Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
int n = sc.nextInt();
Internally Scanner:

Reads input

Uses regex parsing

Splits tokens

Converts to integer

Does safety checks

👉 That regex parsing makes it slow.

For small input → OK
For 200,000+ numbers → TLE

🟢 What BufferedReader Does
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
BufferedReader:

Reads a full line at once

Stores it in memory buffer

Does NOT parse anything

Very minimal overhead

It is just a fast raw reader.

Example:

String line = br.readLine();

This reads the whole line as a string.

Fast.

🔵 Then What Is StringTokenizer?

After reading a full line:

String line = "200000 200000";

We need to split it into numbers.

Instead of using:

line.split(" ")

(which uses regex → slow)

We use:

StringTokenizer st = new StringTokenizer(line);

Then:

int n = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());
int m = Integer.parseInt(st.nextToken());

StringTokenizer is much faster because:

No regex

Just splits by space

Lightweight

⚡ Speed Comparison
Method	Speed
Scanner	Slow
split()	Medium
BufferedReader + StringTokenizer	Fast
